but Battle Creek proper is a mile
from here, it has three or four thousand
inhabitants, & is quite a pretty little
place, this Institution stands on an
elevation, and commands a lovely
view of all the country round. I was
here during the Fall. & had the benefit
of the Autumn foliage, I have been
here since the 21st Sept, and have been
very ill, for some time. I scarcely expected
I would live to leave here, but I am some
better now, but the improvement is very
slow, of course I do not enjoy being
here away from all friends, but I thought
it was better so for a time till I was a little
stronger, as I dislike giving trouble to 
my kind friends - my Chicago friends
were very much against my leaving
them, & cheer my solitude by frequent
letters. I intended going to England in the 
Summer and afterwards in the Fall, but my
ill health prevented my doing so.
Completed

I hope to go as soon as spring comes
I expect I will be well enough by that time
When I thought of going in the fall
I wrote to cousin Mary Everett asking 
her if she could help me to get a Boarding
House, where I could remain a few weeks
before sailing, so as to see a little of
New York City, but I received no reply
whether the letter was lost, or whether she 
cannot help me, of course I cannot tell.
I have a mind to try her again, as she
is the only relative or friend I have in
New York City. I have lost her address
and would feel pretty obliged if you
would send it me - I have also 
been surprised not to have received
any letter from you or Janie for so long.
I wrote in April or May last, I gave my
address at 411 West Monroe St, but even
if I had not done so, I know Janie has
been to Utica, & if she wishes to write to me
could have got my address from Fannie
Completed

so I cannot account for your silence in 
any way, except that I have offended
you in some way. I am very sorry if
that is the case, and assure you it had
been done unwittingly.
There are about 150 patients here
I need not have felt lonesome had I been
pretty well and able to enjoy society, for
there are many very agreeable people here
and as it is I have made several
pleasant friends, while I was very ill
nothing could exceed the kindness and 
solicitude of some of the lady patients.
I had only been here two or three weeks then
I was an entire stranger, now I am
not confined to my room, but am able to go
about, The treatment here is very
thorough underscore & excellent underscore, but it was too severe
for me, now I take very much lighter
treatment & fare better, I think the
massages & the electricity are what helps
me mostly. I have had a good many
letters from my Welsh & English friends lately
Completed

they are greatly troubled about me,
for they expected me home in the Fall.
How glad I will be to see their dear
faces again.
I hear from Cousin Mary Ann very
frequently, she is now renting rooms
as she has her niece Ella Roberts
with her. Ella goes to school at Chicago
M A is very anxious to get me back to
Chicago, as she does not think I am
improving sufficiently here but I
am desirous to give this treatment
a little underscore longer chance to work
an improvement. Dr Kellogg says
I will get well two words underscored,
These people are Seventh Day Baptists
We have no real dear old Sunday.
Saturday they keep very strictly
everything is very very two words underscored quiet. There
is no treatment &c &c - Then on our Sunday
everything goes on as usual. And as
we cannot afford to lose two days two words underscored treatment
we have to go in with the stream
Completed

It is a great cause of discontent
and unpleasantness. As people do not stay
((unclear)) here more than they are absolutely
obliged to - did you receive the
circular of this place that Isent
you? Lord might ((unclear))
be all expected to ((unclear)) at eight
and ((unclear)) always ready now. Ihave
benefited much by the quiet reset
here, Ido hope you are both well
now, my best to you both and to all
the other friends
Sincerely your cousin
((unclear)) Williams
((unclear)) wrote me that Cousin Edward
was in Chicago. Ifelt so sorry to miss
him. Please give him my love and tell
him so, excuse a badly written and badly
composed letter, Iwrote it last night andwas
a good deal tired, they want me to go
to Davisville on a visit when I go to New York I will 
((unclear)) depend how I am I would have gone there instead
of this place, had their institutions not burnt down
Completed

Osawatown Apr 10th 1892
Dear Aunts
Your letter was 
received last night and
hasten to reply lest I should
neglect it as I have been
doing for so long. We had
a severe wind storm here
on the date you mentioned
and from your description I
think that it was about as
hard in Mich., as here
We did not hear of any serious
damage in the country about
here. The wind did some havoc
in Osawatown? It tipped the
sidewalks from Mr Drysdales?
corner to unclear corner
over entire without breaking it
Completed

We hear from J Eddie quite often through 
his father I suppose you are anxiously 
awaiting your turn for a visit
We were taken by surprise when he told
us of his plans he didn't tell us until
Sunday evening and he started Monday
he thought his father had spoken of it
while he was at Anthony? we were sorry
to have him so far away but
hope he can be near you hope he
will have good success and be able
to come and see us before long +
bring his aunties with him
Our school opened unclear with the
same teacher as last term a Miss
Krimbal of Paola. Our neighbours are
all well I think. Mrs Lesenden has
just returned from a trip east
to Elysium? to see a sick sister
I haven't seen her since she came
home, Mrs Snyden came to see us
one day last week had a very nice
visit - she is a great -talker. Mr
Thrlthial? + family have moved to
Iowa? & rented the farm to a
man from Mo? Olive has picked
Completed

Dear Aunties Robert has to many
chores to do to day to be able
to write a very long letter so
I will gladly finish his sheet.
We have a mullato boy working
for us this summer "he is a boy
that Sydney Duncan brought up"
he was not feeling well to day
so didn't help R any. We are milk-
ing about 21 or 22 cows now Betty had
a nice heifer calf to day our Mary
Ann cow had twins this spring
we didn't raise either as they were
small and came very early. Do
you remember Aunt unclear how wild
Lofty? used to be when we went
to the unclear she is as gentle as
any of the cows now + that is
saying a gooddeal as they are all very
quiet after getting acquainted with
us. We did not go to church to day
it is windy + cold + rained alittle
this morning
Completed

The wind also did about $100. damage to the osage valley flock or (new bank) the building is built of brick with a square roof. Around the roof there was built a cornice about 4 ft high to protect the building against fire. On the south side this Cornice was blowing in on the roof. There were several small buildings blown down but no serious damage done. I twas a strong wind but nothing frightful about it here. We have planted potatoes. We have also planted onions, radish, beets and soe other early vegetables. Grass is beginning to start and some of the trees are looking green. Our pie plant are nearly large enough to use. 
Libbie has finished my letter so I will merely say that we are all well and as happy as need be We are having what I call our disagreeable weather windy and rainy Love to you all 
Your nephew R.H. Everett
Completed

Osawatown Dec 6-/91
Dear Aunties
We think it about 
time we hear from you + I think
in order to get a letter I will 
have to write one. We are all real
well, + hope you re the same.
Are you having very cold weather
We think we have had some
pretty cold weather for this time
of the year in Kansas at least
we felt it - very much the
house is pretty cold a good deal
of cold coming through the 
the floor although we had it
bauked and have you heard of
the new bed rooms we have it
took a little extra fire to warm
Completed

them or rather it - as it is in 
our room unclear downstairs +
will have a room up stairs
when it is finished we find
it very convenient as it is.
We are making about 9 lbs of
butter a day, churn every day
but Sunday. We haven't any
fresh cows yet.
We expect to enjoy a good
visit from J.E. soon we
hope to hear from him to
day.
We have two men here now
shucking corn getting up wood
unclear I think they are both unclear
unclear to you Aunt Mary their
names are Jed Cogswell + Lewis Clark
Robert has fixed up the frame
unclear barn for all the horses taking
the partition out where Harveys unclear
was making more rooms and he
Completed

Galesburg Dec 20 1858
Dearest Annie
Do forgive my long silence. It is not dear Annie because I have forgotten you but I have been very busy studying striving to improve my mind. You know my dislike to letter writing and if it were not for my great desire to hear from you I fear I should not now write.
You wished to know about the Seminary Miss Wilcox is the Preceptress and has about
Completed

30 young ladies under her charge. I believe they are quite well pleased with her. They have monthly receptions and the young ladies are permitted to invite all of their friends and are very pleasant I hear. their rules are very strict for the young ladies are not allowed to go out or receive company any evening except Friday. I do not call at the Seminary quite as often as I did last winter for I have not as man friends there now. Mrs. Sheppard is the music teacher in the Seminary. The College is any thing but prospourrs the number of Students daily diminishing. I do not know whether I can tell you any ? news or not the streets are just as muddy as when
Completed

you were here. We have had a little snow which I enjoyed very much in having a delightful ride with a company of ten. How is sleighing in New York? Mother is not at all well she will work though she would love to see you as well as my self. Grandma is at Knox Corners we do miss her very much. The Farnham's family are all quite well - they are in their new house. Mary was writing me not long ago and asked about you and I sent much love. As for myself I am at home and quite well studying with my friend Katie Blanchard - we recite to Sister Maz? who has returned from Chicago. We study Arithmec Grammer Spelling and the history which your Sister Jennie gave me.
Completed

I have nearly finished it the second time we also read Bullins? Ancient History and study Music.  Dont you think I have my hands full? I had a present of a pair of Canary birds, one of them is a beautiful singer & he is charming or rather distracting me with his music. Give much love to Jennie for me and indeed you may to all the family for I almost feel acquainted with them because of my great friendship for you  After reading your letter over I find I have not answered all your questions Mrs. Prentice keeps the boarding house. Nellie has not returned but nearly all the rest of the Girls are here. but as it is nearly three which is our dinner hour I must

Miss A. L. Everett
Remsen
N.Y.
Completed

Turin, Aug. 8th, 1867
My Dear Sister,

 I am going to undertake to answer one of those unanswered letters you have lying in your portfolio. If it is not done satisfactorily to you, I will let you try it next time. I sent a note home with William which I wrote that morning before I was fairly awake and I hardly know what I did write. I hope I did not put any frightful dream in it. 

I would like to know how you are enjoying this warm weather We find it difficult to "keep cool." Have our cousins from Chicago come yet? I am in hopes to see them when I come home. Should be very sorry to miss seeing them. I think Cynthia wrote me when they were coming but I have forgotten
Completed

I think we had better start Tuesday morning. If you would prefer starting Tuesday afternoon please let me know Sat. We are going to have the company of two ladies besides our company as far as Springfield; Mrs. R., of whom I spoke in my other letter, and a young lady from Lowville. I hope nothing will occur to hinder us from going this time as it is third time we have set for the said trip East I hope you have marked out the route you would prefer as I have given it no thought since I was home. Has Mary concluded to go with us. I wonder if she went to the Falls with the Penymynydd company. 

Good bye. I hope to see you Monday morning. Tell the girls to save some rain water as will want my vest and linen coat done up when I get home. From Your Brother,
Completed

Dear Anna

 We received your letter Saturday night, and are very sorry for your perplexity in regard to the piano. Your first letter was received when we were most hurried with Cenhadwr, and as it was several days before our hurry was over, it was some time before we cold ascertain anything about the probability of our success in obtaining scholars for you. We were very sorry on your account, but this is our explanation. Saturday P.M. Sarah and I went to the village and called on Lina's mother, also at the two Mrs. Pughs, at Douglass's and Montagues. Maria's mother said she would like to have her take lessons, but did
Completed

not speak very decidedly about it. Mrs. H. Pugh says they are somewhat bothered in money affairs now. Mr Pugh, you know is just starting in business on his own account and many of his customers ar slow to pay. If it were not for that she thought she would like to have her daughter learn. She thought B. Morgan's little boy would take lessons. His parents are very anxious for him to take lessons on the melodian. He now plays well on the violin, and has musical talent. Neither Mr. Douglass or Mr. Montague's people appeared to think that their girls would take lessons. Isabel says their teacher Mr. Jenkyn, intends to have a piano in his school next term, which opens next Meonday. A lady from Boonville, I believe is to give lessons on it  She has been trying some time to get a class. Linas
Completed

mother says the feel the pressure of the times very much. Their property is City property. Lina is quite occupied, attending school, knitting for soldiers &c. If it were otherwise she would like much to have Lina take lesson  We think Ruth would certainly take lessons,, but have not seen her since Mother wrote. We think She and Maria (if she takes lessons) would like quite as well, and perhaps prefer to take lessons on the Melodian. Mrs. Pugh promised to speak to Mrs. Morgan and also to R. Roberts people about Mary. The district school is very flourishing now, and takes the children's time, still we think if you once got started with a few, you might soon have more. We spoke to Ellen Owen. She did not know but thought you might succeed Maria Edward is not at home
Completed

Feb. 3 1876
Dear cousin -

 What has become of Uncle Eddie & Aunt Mali? have they got snowed in? Are you all well? Have Uncle E & Aunt M been at your house yet We expected them last week and are and shall expect them until they come. Lovingly 

F. E L.
Are all well there We haven't found Aunt Anna's pictures yet 
F. E L.
Completed

above are a later editors's comment and someone else's retraction of the crossing-out; letter follows below.
Remsen April illegible 1880
Dear Aunt Anna
Your very welcome letter of April 13 was received promptly. Frankie was very much delighted to receive it, the same as myself. I have been to Uncle Lewis' making a dress for Aunt Jane last week. They are all well there. I have been at sevrral places near home sewing, and have been to Utica to. We are busy house cleaning these days we want to get through before Louisa commences her school. She is going to teach at the coverd brigge school. Her school opens the first Monday in May.
Completed

Tell John Eddie that I scarcily think Frankie will attend school this Summer but she teaches school in Mother's bedroom and talks about her scholars tells what caprice they have been doing during the day. She has such queer mames for her scholars that a stranger would almost believe her. What Frank says she wants from New York is a present. She wots me to tell, that Aunt Laura gave her two dresses and I will send you a sample of cashmere we have in the house, do you think it would make a pretty dress for her trimmed with lace of the same shade and blue ribon bows. She went to Prospect to-day with Uncle John and Aunt Bessy to see little Bola Haskins before she goes away. Dr. Haskins is going to Colorado. they start Monday. I believe
Completed

I told in my last letter that John Roberts is going to Sioux City, Iowa I was sorry to here that Aunt Sarah has been sick I hope she is better before this time. How does Aunt Jennie stand it. I suppose she is having a good time. Of course Aunt Mary is well for Doctors have no right to be sick at all. We will let you know as soon as the weather gets warm here. it is quite cold yet. But the roads are pretty good now the new minister will preach for the first time at Remsen to morrow his name is Smith he is quite a young man about 22 years, I think.
Proff. Gardner of Whitestown is dead funeral to be Monday Jessie Hughs is coming to make us a visit next vacation
Completed

Frankie wants you to bring little Grace Jones home with you, so she can have her to play with her, Frank will have to have more practice before she can write a letter But I am quite certain that she will come up to this very soon. 

Please write soon again and tell the rest to write. 
We all write in sending our love to you all. 
I remain as ever your friend and niece
 J. E. Everett

Oh yes Franks dog is name is Topsy her doll is name is Goldie blue Eyes.
Completed

Turin Sept. 13th 1880
Dear Sisters
It is now after nine Edward has not come home from the store yet, he has been over the river to day as usual. We went up to see about his lumber last Sat. they say they can't saw unless it rains I was glad to see the rain come Mon. Lumber has come up and if he could get it out in two or three weeks he could
Completed

make about $300 on it and he could tell better what he wold do this coming winter. I rec'd a postal from Mary this Wed. noon asking if he could be at the meeting in R- Wed to day. I have seen nothing of you & Anna yet aren't you coming back? & if that Cousin comes she can come up here. Carroll & Charlie go to school and it is rather lonely for me though I keep busy. That pattern I spoke of was that p. I made my lace on I don't know as I shall make
Completed

another now I did think I would make one for Mother  Mrs. Karliskint? was here yester washed & partly irined? & done since? swerpring? E- has first came & brought in some grapes you see what you miss by not being here
Mon. morn. I did not finish this as I am not very smart? Carroll or Charlie will stay home with me to day. Aren't you unclear comeing up here before long I do wish you would come & stay 'till you go to New York write us where you will be
Completed

I have not seen Aunt Kate to speak to her yet I don't think she has been out much of late several have said that when you come back they are going to call on you, I was down to Mrs. Eames last week she was well Mrs. W- is getting along nicely. Hope to hear from you soon come if you can with much love from each of us to you all how is the baby? Is Lewis better? Mate? 
added at top:
H. left her silver paper shall I send it?
Completed

Turin Oct. 2nd 1880
Dear Sisters
It is Sat. morn & I thought I would drop you a few lines. I thought E- had written before now he has been very busy, packing up T.J. old goods Charlie has rented the store for 2?8? years taking possession yesterday. T.J. has gone to Albany yes- I went with E. down to Cousin Emma Johnson stayed all day I have not been very well the fore part of the week am better now. Carroll is sick found him feverish last night
Completed

he has some fever this morning Last Sat. I asked Dr. Johnson for his bill he brought is to me on Wednesday & to my surprise it was only $30.30 for about four months treatment some weeks coming 2 or 3 times we thought it wold be about $80. Edward said about apples if it would not be so much trouble & work for you a barrell of apples would be very acceptable Edward was over to see about his lumber. The man said if it continued to rain he would get it out in two weeks. I was in hopes it would continue to rain
Completed

I hope week after next you & Anna will be here come if you can. George Prichard sleeps here nights as they have no room over to A.W. for him Ed. told him he might come for a week till he could get another place it has been a week today  Mrs. K- comes once in two weeks & washes & irons for us we get along nicely. I only weight 128 now, E is very well Charlie is my right hand man. Do you hear from John E.?
Completed

Your slips are doing nicely Jimmie brought us a bag of apples last night they wee very acceptable apples seem to be plenty they are from 25-30 up to 80 cents a bushel. You see we have not gone to Kansas I have felt all of the time that if it was best for us to go the lumber would get read to start off hope to hear from you soon we could till? the difference in wanting?
Love from each of us to you all from E. &. M-
Completed

embossed: HAMILTON
New York Dec 3/81
Dear Home Folkes;

The little reminder was welcome today I was pleased to hear that S. is improving, I hope she will eat ever so much & gain strength next week we have had a very pleasant day. Shall be anxious to know how the blinds look. Are they to be primed with green or some other Hope the paint will not be offensive. Met Mrs. Thomas 38th St. in the cars yesterday She enquired very kindly & sends love
Completed

I have been rather lazy today or should have written earlier in the day. The dining room up stairs is ever so much pleasanter than as we had it before & I have a very quiet time all to myself. Shall make more progress with my studies, but I feel lost somewhat. Went up stairs this afternoon & laid on Mrs. Van Burens? bed. It seemed quite nice & restful. Has S. sat up any more since I? left & how much does she eat & Anna you may take this same question to yourself! Much Much love Mollie
Completed

Buffalo Center Mar 30 1890
Dear Auntie
I thought I would write you a letter. papa killed a gopher yestardy, I found 23 badger holes and one praiarie dogs, I went to Church last sunday. One of the Indians came to sell wood. I saw two praiarie wolves yestarday I saw a flock of wild geese and praiarie chichens. I went with papa to Draw hay yestar day. how do you feel. we are living with Uncle Wills for [unclear] now. we got a lever from Aunt Jennie since we came here.
good bye,
Lewis.
Completed

Buffalo Center Apr. 1st 1890
Dear Aunt Alicia.
I have only time to write just a word this time. Will is going to the post office and I will send just a word to let you know that we are alive and well. We are sowing wheat and Consequently are quite busy The weather is quite pleasant but it is too Cold for vegetation to Start yet. The Country about here is far from being level and still farther from being like the Country back there look from your house to Capel Uchaf and imaging not a tree stump or stone and you will have an idea of some of the prarie about here the Claim I have taken is much more level than that. Hoping to hear from you soon I am your nephew R. H. Everett
Completed

Sprague, Wash.

Sept. 18, 1890

Dear Aunt Anna:

I suppose you are having a visit just now from Holden, Hattie & Eva. Wish we lived a little nearer, so we could be there too. I often think of the pleasant weeks I spent there last summer. It hardly seems possible that we can be so far away now. I have been meaning to write you ever since we came. Am sorry we could not have had that visit before we left Phoenix. We find things here very different from those in the 

Did Hattie receive the letter I wrote her, directed to Petoskey? We have received no Independents from the N.Y. office as yet.
Completed

East, with some thing favorable and others not so pleasant. We have plenty of fruit out here, of the best kind, peaches, pears, plums, apples, grapes, &c &c The prices are about the same this season as in the East, for fruit, especially peaches, has not been so abundant as usual. Apples, however are much higher being 5 cts. a pound, the same as pears, peaches being 10 cts. We bought splendid large yellow peaches at $1.00 a box and just ate 8 or 10 quarts, about the same of pears, and today I got a box of prunes for canning, at the same price. These resemble blue plums, but are larger & sweeter. They are very nice to eat in the hand. Most of the fruit comes from the Snake river, some from Oregon.
Completed

We like the climate here so far, except the dust. The air is fresh and bracing, and the nights always cool. Think my health has improved somewhat since coming. Azia was very homesick at first, but has got more acquainted and used to it now. The baby has been cutting his double teeth this summer, and has not been very well. His head seems to trouble him, and we have to be careful of him for fear he will have more fits. This morning he sat for his picture, which we hope will be good. He has not had any taken since the time I was at your house. We are hoping to go to Spokane Falls tomorrow for a week's visit if Clarence is well enough. Last night he frightened us by crying and being
Completed

feverish, so that it was quite late before he got to sleep. We give him bromide and chloral for his nervousness. There is no homeopathic physician here, for which we are sorry. He does not walk alone yet or talk, altho he is nearly 20 months old. We have a small parsonage here, next to the church, supplied with city water, and the church is lighted with electricity. We have a fine choir, and good S. school. There are a good many Welsh people around here, and some in the church. W. Griffiths, the Baptist minster of Utica, was here a short time ago. He is editor of a Welsh magazine. We hope you are all well and prospering. Hope you will write us soon. With love to all including the visitors. J.H. Butler.
Completed

Olpe, Kas. Feb. 19/91.
Dear Aunt Anna,-
I am sending you to-day photos of Carroll and Ray. Carroll's picture was taken last June and Ray's the mid--dle of Jannary. It is very quiet in the story to-day, as it has been raining all day. Yesterday was very cold and it snowed all day. More snow than we have had in all winter. I suppose you know that Kansas is subject to most extreme changes, last Monday for instance; every in the morning is was so warm that is was uncomfortable to stay in the house without the win-dows or doors open, and in the
Completed

afternoon it was so cold that it was most impossible to ride faceing the wind. Carroll hasn't been home from school since the holidays. To-morrow will be the most eventful and looked foward to with the most inter--est by all of the college students of Kansas, of all of the college year. It being the Annual Inter-collegiate Oratorical [coutes?] of Kansas. This year it will be held in the Whitley opera house, of Emporia under the management of the State Normal. Five colleges, the State Normal of Emporia and the State Uni-versity of Lawrence will be rep--resented. The colleges which will be represented are sit-uated at the following places; Emporia (Presbyterian), Topeka
Completed

(Washburn, a Congregational institu-tion, Baldwin Cy. (Methodist) Ottawa and Salina. The Mendelssohn Quar-tette of the Emporia College in which Carroll sings 2nd Bass, will sing at the contest. The admission is seventy five cents, and there was such a demand for tickets that all were sold before Tuesday. I was lucky enough to get one. Carroll sings in the choir of the First Presby-terian church of Emporia and gets one dollar a Sunday. To-day is Eddies seventh birthday, he weighs nearly as much as Robbie and learns fast in school. Harry has just got over a siege of pneumonia. I have not been going to school at all this win-ter, but have been kept pretty busy in the store. Trade has
Completed

been much better this winter than last, about fifty percent. It is not because the so- called Peoples party or farmers alliance party has got in power but if they were not in power in this state business would be a great deal better for the reason that farmers that have mortgages coming due cannot get them renewed, nor can they borrow any money, because money loan-ers are afraid of what the Alliance legislature will do. Well as I am nearing the bottom of this page I will have to close With love from all I'll bid adieu. York Nephew
{Chas H. Everett?]
Completed

Alder Creek
Dec. 27, 1891
Dear Cousins;-

  I wrote in my last letter that I would write again in a week, but after sending it I came to the conclusion that it would take you a week to read it, if indeed, you would succeed at the end of that time, then I thought you would need some time to recruit after the punishment I had inflicted on you. 
  And I didn't feel at all flattered as I expected I would over the idea that you would be looking forward to the next issue from the pen, or rather pencil
Completed

2
of Mr. Everett!! but felt ashamed to tink I had sent such a horrid scribble, but my excuse was that I was short of paper and I wnated to send all the news I could for two cents, but I will try to do better this time. I am commencing a new pad and if this isn't enough for me we have another so I feel quite independent as far as paper goes. 

How have you been getting along. I think it is time you wrote to let us know "somethin anyow",
 We have our "ups and down's", about four weeks ago Uncle and Auntie had a sick time: Auntie still feels from it.  it was like Rheumatism in her neck and shoulder, until
Completed

3
she could not move, and now it is my turn I took a hard cold, or had the "Grippe" week before last Wednesday and have barked ever since at first I was so hoarse I could'nt speak and coughed very hard Aunt Annie put flax seed poultice's on my chest an it did me so much good, I think I would of had Pneumonia only they worked over me so faithfully. night before last I coughed for about an hour and a half without stopping and had to sit up in bed all night and last night too. just as soon as I would lie down I would cough so in order to sleep I had to sit up with half a dozen
Completed

pillows to my back and all the remedies we could think of on a table by my bedside, well I think I have written enough about myself, but you know it is a good subject, and I don't know when to stop when I do get hold of a subject that is "throughly good." March 27th/92
Dear Cousins;-

 Your letter of Feb. 2 still unanswered and it is a shame, when I promised to write so often to tell all the news, "but never mind better luck next time." I think when I left off last time I left Aunt Jane sweeping up stairs, well, she hasn't been sweeping all this time for it only took her a few minutes. and I folded and put away some things that had been left, Cousin Marys Ulster I put on the fence and took the carpet beater to it then put it up with tobacco, we found the handle of one of your Fathers and Mothers silver spoons that was broken 

I have lost your address so address by guess hope you will get it
